  "opinion": "As someone who's spent years working with my hands on electrical systems in Lecce, I've seen firsthand how stereotypes can shape people's confidence in technical fields. Stereotype threat—when individuals feel at risk of confirming negative stereotypes about their group—hits hard in STEM because it's often tied to gender, race, or socioeconomic background. For instance, a young woman in my community might hesitate to ask questions in a workshop because she worries her 'lack of math skills' will prove her incapable. This isn't just theory; it's real. I've heard stories from my kids' school where girls avoid science fairs, fearing they'll be judged as 'not smart enough.' But addressing this isn't about fixing people—it's about creating spaces where everyone feels safe to try. In my part-time work, I've started organizing hands-on workshops for local teens, focusing on practical projects like building simple circuits instead of abstract equations. This approach taps into my curiosity and respect for hands-on learning, which aligns with what Buddhism teaches: action without judgment. We should shift the narrative from 'you can't' to 'you belong here.' It’s not about erasing stereotypes but helping people see their potential beyond what others might assume. By fostering community and practical engagement, we can break down those barriers. After all, in Lecce, where the streets are alive with creativity, everyone has a place to contribute—whether you're building a circuit or sketching a photo.",
